Schrodinger said in his 1935 &quot;cat&quot; paper that the &quot;system vector&quot; in his Nobel-winning equation is described in a perfectly deterministic time-continuous way, but an irreducible uncertainty occurs because the &quot;system vector&quot; does *not* have a one-to-one mapping with physical &#39;Reality.&#39;
His lectures from the 1950s further clarify this point.  And modern &#39;quantum field theory&#39; agrees: irreducible uncertainty, but not a blurred cat.
